the following best describes the mechanism of action of gonadotrophin-releasing hormone agonists?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Initial stimulation followed by suppression of gonadotrophin release","Initial suppression followed by increased gonadotrophin release","Direct inhibition of gonadal hormone synthesis","Persistent stimulation of gonadotrophin release","Immediate and sustained suppression of gonadotrophin release"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EGonadotrophin-releasing hormone agonists work through a biphasic mechanism. The \u003Cstrong\u003Einitial stimulation followed by suppression of gonadotrophin release\u003C/strong\u003E occurs because continuous exposure to the agonist leads to downregulation of pituitary receptors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInitial suppression followed by increased gonadotrophin release\u003C/strong\u003E would be ineffective for treating hormone-dependent conditions as it would ultimately increase hormone levels. The actual mechanism begins with stimulation, not suppression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect inhibition of gonadal hormone synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect; these drugs act primarily on the pituitary gland by binding to gonadotrophin-releasing hormone receptors. They do not directly affect hormone production in the gonads.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPersistent stimulation of gonadotrophin release\u003C/strong\u003E occurs initially, but continuous receptor activation leads to desensitisation and downregulation. If stimulation remained persistent, it would worsen rather than treat hormone-dependent conditions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate and sustained suppression of gonadotrophin release\u003C/strong\u003E overlooks the important initial stimulatory phase that occurs before receptor downregulation. Understanding this biphasic response is crucial as it can cause temporary symptom flare-up.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe initial stimulatory phase can cause a temporary worsening of symptoms (flare effect) before the therapeutic suppressive effects begin. This is particularly important in conditions like prostate cancer where the flare may need to be managed with additional medications.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Gonadotrophin-releasing hormone agonists initially stimulate luteinising hormone and follicle-stimulating hormone release from the pituitary.","Continuous exposure to gonadotrophin-releasing hormone agonists leads to receptor downregulation and suppression of gonadotrophin secretion.","The initial stimulatory effect of gonadotrophin-releasing hormone agonists can cause a temporary worsening of hormone-dependent conditions."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63106"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17084"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63106","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63106"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-07T20:03:13+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-07T20:06:02+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9774"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77593"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"http